The president hesitated for three months but in the absence of a better option, he at least swindled the general of 10,000 soldiers.
He managed to extirpate the promise of an additional 5,000 from Europe, even though he originally had 10,000.
What brings the most problems to Obama's entire strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the armies from Afghanistan within 18 months and to complete this whole process within three years. Obama's entire doctrine brings more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that a halving increase will bring the same results as the increase in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honour the agreements.
The Afghan situation stands out by the exact opposite — no one can be relied on and no treaty is respected.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing their leadership on a day-to-day basis, depending on what suits them.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will remain only a powder behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
It is particularly complex to balance the interests of the various ethnic groups in view of the lack of clarity about the relationship, which is further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a "early-to-act state", which is the basic purpose of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
Obama's strategy's time horizon is perplexed by his voluntarism.
In the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is now on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic heart out of reality can be convinced that the little soldiers sent into the tumult of war with a view to their "return home" will bring there a real miracle.
From a political point of view, defining a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will consider it the indirect admission of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that Europeans' willingness to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is moving towards the negative.
European politicians do not know or want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the Hindu Kush mountains.
Another factor capable of radically altering the situation is the evolution of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the strengthened sanctions do not affect Iranians, the Americans will face the very difficult issue of resolving the problem through the use of military force.
This will have to be answered, for example, at a time when, according to Obama, America will come to the victorious withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
Each such solution will, however, result in a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
Obama's only rustin is the fact that there are three years left until the presidential election and therefore there is still enough time for him to plan a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
