The United Nations group has draft emission reduction plans
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- so far characterized by disorganized assignments and mutual recriminations -- has returned to the spotlight on Friday, as a result of the publication of a document highlighting the ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations supporting most of the burden in the coming time.
The text that could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles, as much as it informed the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in the time-consuming negotiations, with more than 100 leaders from around the world arriving next week in Copenhagen.
Written by a UN ad hoc working group, the text does not say how rich countries would give to the poor to withstand global warming, both in the short and long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed and emerging new economies could reduce their carbon production and what would be the upper limit of the global temperature increase that leaders would be willing to tolerate.
It gives great flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Representative in Washington of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN Executive Secretary-General on climate change, Yvo de Boer, described as "the full picture".
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 2020, by 25 to 45 per cent from 1990 levels, while the major developing countries, over the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 per cent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions by between 50 and 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union also relaunched the negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to withstand floods and drought or to avoid deforestation.
On Friday, however, the same verbal altercations took place, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, US Climate Negotiator, rejected any discussion that forced the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, compared to the voluntary efforts of the major emerging economies, if not funded by developed countries.
This change is a signal that the Obama administration is becoming harder on China than the Bush administration was two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without the efforts and actions of the main developing countries, says Stern, who also regretted that the text does not insist enough to ensure that the reductions could be verified by external observers.
Stern commented an hour after China's Deputy Foreign Minister, He Yafei, said that the US chief negotiator, either lacked "good sense" or was "extremely irresponsible" for saying earlier this week that the US would not help China financially to fight global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the major world powers at stake, flaws have emerged both within the Third World and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about saving individual economies than saving the planet, with China and the United States arguing about their respective obligations, while poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives of acting more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that the main powers were fighting to find out who should bear the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even though the vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to make the major emitters responsible for their actions.
It is really a game in which is developed a new economic hegemony, said Ulate, who is also Climate Advisor for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries that are more vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they will continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most key participants say that negotiations will lead at least to a political agreement.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States drafted a 24-page treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, Head of the Climate Unit of the European Commission, said that the action of small island states "has put political pressure on the entire political process", partly because they are now unified and they are asking emerging economies such as China and India to act.
The discussions became an urgent matter, as delegates focused on the fact that they had to resolve most of the outstanding issues before Heads of Government reached agreement.
High-level officials such as the Indian Minister of the Environment, Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister descended from their aircraft and rushed into the Bella Center building to attend closed meetings and information conferences in order to be able to make complaints that will be studied during the following week.
The real image of the gathering -- during which 13,000 people enter and leave the Congress Hall every day -- guitar player activists present night shows mocking countries that they believe are betraying and that proposals are written and distributed on paper rather than by email -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the greats' courts, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice President for Global Policy at Conservation International.
The heavy goods vehicles are coming.
