No one else has to act in her place," said the representative of the Public Prosecutor's Office, Marie-Chrsitine Daubigney.
The court finally decided that it would decide once the trial had taken place on the admissibility of Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers.
Management revolution or end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain...
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies towards its employees, recalls the position of companies vis-à-vis consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of making employees adhere to "values" determined from above as it once was, of imposing on consumers products designed by the technicians of the factory.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering the markets in the place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from the factors of customer preferences returns regularly!
Demobilization of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects managers in particular.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all the company's intellectual functions, including R&D and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, EI "requires all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires a commitment on the part of employees that authoritarian management revenue completely contradicts.
That is why we call for a managerial revolution that would put employees at the centre of the company's concerns on the same footing as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Will internal opinion surveys—like the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees—incite this revolution in managerial practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First of all, because I was able to see that, in the face of a new situation, every structure finally, after many detours, gets to do first and foremost... what it has always done.
- Then, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – increases proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behaviour.
Coming from the major engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, out of intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the American "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of study and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "leviers" (sic) of the commitment of executives, a recent survey by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reinforces the leaders in a posture of mechanistic governance, inappropriate to the world of today.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises, presupposes adopting a finalist vision of human behaviour.
It consists in integrating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental observation: for employees, commitment for the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to realize part of their dreams, their ambitions, their projects.
At present, only the studies resulting from the Reasoning Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their business on the basis of a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the business, to evaluate what it offers them to carry out their life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, business leaders can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and hand over their human resources management "to the place".
They thus create a favourable ground for the concerted development of robust and effective economic intelligence.
Oslo Speech: "Just War" Worth Right-Walking Praise to Obama
On Friday, the American right welcomed Barack Obama's previous speech in Oslo, who was pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize winner defended the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
The Conservatives, who brokered Obama's award on October 9, applauded the presidential speech this time, as did Sarah Palin, former vice-president in the 2008 elections.
I liked what he said, said Ms. Palin, a geriatric of the right wing of the Republican Party, to the daily US Today, adding that she herself had addressed the topic of war "sometimes necessary" in her memoirs that have just been published.
War is, of course, the last thing I think the Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
These terrorists must be stopped all over there, she said.
Obama, who inherited two wars from his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, worked Thursday in Oslo to justify the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send 30,000 more soldiers to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, considered that the president had done "very good work" in Oslo.
I found that the speech was really very good, welcomed the former Speaker of the House of Representatives, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential statement.
On some sides, I found this speech quite historic, said Mr. Gingrich, interviewed on the radio show "The Takeaway".
The former elected member, considered by some to be a possible candidate for the Republican nomination for the 2012 presidential election, said he was delighted to have seen "a left-wing president" remind the members of the Nobel Committee "that they would not be free and would not be able to award a peace prize if the use of force did not exist".
For Michael Gerson, former penist of George W. Bush converted columnist at the Washington Post, Obama delivered "a very American speech".
