Turkish justice dissolves the pro-Kurdish party, a decision with serious consequences
On Friday, the Turkish Constitutional Court dissolved the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that was immediately followed by anger in the Kurdish community, in the south-eastern part of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which had just reached out to the Kurdish community in an attempt to put an end to 25 years of conflict.
The Party for a Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved as it had become a "foyer of activities detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity", told the press the president of the Court Hasim Kiliç, after four days of deliberations.
