The cradle of dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 meters long by 1.50m high, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was provided with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended with sickle claws and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would not have had anything exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin reports and his colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine, Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs with these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which at the time was part of the supercontinent's land, the Pangea, and was towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says that the discovery of Tawa sheds new light on the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
Indeed, he tells us about the relationship, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
In 2006, Sertling Nesbitt undertook excavations with other paleontologists at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and member of the excavation team tells that sometimes they find a dozen bones in one day which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating from the Trias.
Scientists soon realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
The excavations revealed the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories about the beginnings of dinosaur evolution.
The researchers named him Tawa after the word Hopi Indians for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is a very exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Trias are extremely rare and are limited to a few incomplete bone fragments.
Not all paleontology experts share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery to be particularly spectacular, but he points out that it allows to confirm certain theories concerning the beginnings of dinosaur evolution.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
However, most of the oldest fossils are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the very first dinosaurs.
The experts wonder, among other things, at what time the saurians divided into three major evolutionary groups: the theropods (carnivores) which include the tyrannosaure and the velociraptor which appeared later and which descend from the birds, the sauropods, quadrupeds at the long neck, and those related to them and the herbivores ornithisches, which include species such as triceratops and stegosaure.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa is one of the first theropods.
This species presents an interesting report of both primitive and developed characteristics, known as S. Nesbitt.
Researchers found evidence that Tawa hallae had small aerial bags in its bones at the skull, as did the birds that are descendants of theropods.
These small pockets of air make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It appears that in Tawa hallae the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small aerial bags in its bones.
Since the related lineage of the immense sauropods also possessed aerial bags and a light frame, it can be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
As the most primitive known dinosaurs lived in South America, researchers concluded that the saurians had appeared there.
As a result, the three major evolutionary lines divided and spread from South America to the rest of the world, that is to say, all the land that formed the Pangeal Supercontinent.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the paleontologists team also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot descend from a common ancestor who would have migrated, advance the researchers.
Alan Turner of the Museum of Natural History in New York and co-author of Science Studies magazine said there would have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says that there is an even older species, silesaure, which lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him this could give an erroneous view because there are a large number of fossils of dinosaurs in South America that have been preserved while there is virtually no one on other continents.
On the other hand, how did dinosaurs manage to become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary era when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch, is still a mystery today.
At the time of the Trias, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of current crocodiles and many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Trias dinosaurs spread over the entire planet, thus promoting the development of many new species, while others, which were related to them, disappeared between the Trias and Jurassic.
Such success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a massive extinction that the dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles would have disappeared.
Or else, dinosaurs were better suited and were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
In any case, such success is not eternal.
150 million years later, a group of animals which had also developed during the Trias and which since then has been vegetating in the shadows: mammals.
