75% of working mothers have had work problems due to maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for young women who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study "Fecundity and professional career of women in Spain", carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey, carried out on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no room for doubt: 75 per cent of working mothers have had limited professional careers because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences in the beginning of married life and the number of children, whether or not the woman is working and the type of job she is employed.
Those who do not work outside the home, work part-time or have little stable work, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are pushing back into marriage and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 who have a fixed job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after moving into a couple. This figure rises to 4.1 among those who work in the public sector."These data show that women in stable employment needed more time in their lives to get it, which led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised largely influences maternity, but less the date of the beginning of the common life," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that widens the gap between the marriage age of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they marry and have their first child later.
The difference also persists among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years respectively on average.
"Another distinction also emerges between women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed elementary education marry and have their first child before finding stable employment, those who have completed middle or higher education reverse this program and give priority to obtaining stable work as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child," says Delgado.
