Sales of light commercial vehicles are increasing
After almost two years, the light commercial vehicle market begins to see some light at the end of the tunnel.
The 9,425 vehicles registered in November in Spain represent an increase of 12.6% compared to 2008 and, more importantly, they represent the first increase after 22 consecutive months of decrease, according to the figures of the employers' union of the Anfac manufacturers and Ganvam, that of the dealers.
However, the good news should be nuanced, since the reference used for comparison in November 2008 was particularly bad, with a 60 % decrease compared to the previous year.
As a result, despite the rebound of last month, registrations accumulated during these 11 months are 40% below those of the previous year.
Since January, by adding all vehicles that fall into the light commercial vehicle category (from passenger cars, pick-up trucks, vans, light vans and light chassis trucks) 95,853 have been sold.
The big clouds that most affect their demand have not dissipated. Indeed, although they are also purchased by private individuals, most purchases are made by small or medium-sized enterprises, which in almost 100% of cases pay with external financing.
Thus, in addition to the restrictions involved in limiting bank loans, there are other factors to be added, such as the increase in the unemployment rate or the persistence of the bad economic situation.
In view of this situation and the difference between passenger vehicles, aid for the purchase of 2000E has been scarce.
In addition to private individuals, self-employed persons and SMEs wishing to acquire a light commercial vehicle of less than 3.5 tonnes with a CO2 emission level of not more than 160 grams per kilometre may also benefit, but the number of operations speaks for itself.
Yesterday, at Ganvam, the need for the administration to pay particular attention to these vehicles and also to industrial vehicles (trucks and buses) was reiterated.
