Emergency brake aid is now mandatory
As has happened with the ABS anti-lock brake system and as will take place with the ESP stability check, emergency brake assist systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
They are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a waiting period has been set until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measure, imposed by the European Union, is to strengthen pedestrian protection, even if, by its mode of action, it can also help to avoid many rear impacts.
The emergency brake assistant acts by increasing the brake pressure in the event of an emergency detected by the system thanks to the driver's kick.
But the latter does not always keep the pressure to the end.
According to a study carried out by the Bosch car component manufacturer, one third of the drivers involved in an accident could not press the brake before the collision, and half of them did not take advantage of its full strength.
