Distribution
This apparent paradox is explained by UEFA's complex money-sharing procedure.
For this year, the organization chaired by Michel Platini plans to win 1,090 million thanks to the Champions League.
Of this amount, the UEFA will spend 413.1 million on fixed payments: each of the 20 clubs that participated in the classification games (among which the Atlético of Madrid) received 2.1 million.
In addition, those who managed to participate received only 3.8 million to be there, in addition to 550 00 euros for each match played.
There is also a bonus in case of victory (800,000 euros) and equality (400,000 for each team). Those who arrive in the eighth of the final receive three million each, the eight teams who arrive in the quarter of the final receive 3.3 million.
The last four teams will each receive 4 million.
And the champion will win 9 million, against the 5.2 received by the other finalist.
Thus, under fixed payments, a club will earn at least 7.1 million, and a maximum of 31.2 million.
On the other hand, the Barça pocketed 2.5 million for winning the European Super Cup in August.
But in addition, there are variable payments, to which 337.8 million are spent.
This money is distributed according to the proportional value of each television market.
The Spanish market is one of the most important, and has four seats.
The champion of the previous year pocketes 40% of the allocated money, 30% for the second, 20% for the third and 10% for the fourth.
