New tools for car expertise
In these days of bad weather and accidents, car garages are not the only winners.
Every day, thousands of cars that have suffered a loss are brought back to a garage, where an expert must assess the damage suffered and the cost of repair.
Each claim is different, and calculating the cost of parts and labour time can be a long and complex work.
Calculating by hand the cost of a repair between 20,000 and 30,000 euros, including parts and labour can take two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the assistance of the latest IT tools, it would be a matter of minutes.
This is why almost 100% of experts use this type of system.
Providers of services and solutions for disaster assessment and maintenance are dedicated to collecting information provided by manufacturers, then processing it and offering it to their customers as a useful tool.
In Spain, Audatex, of the North American group Solera, is the leading company; 80% of the estimates are made with its products.
The other companies competing in the field of assessment tools and the development of information on the sector are GtMotive and Eurotax.
The work with the data provided by the manufacturers is far from simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, sales manager of Audatex, the company in Spain with 63 manufacturers and importers, and each of them provides them with information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed continues to increase, so that in the last five years more versions, variants and engines have been launched than in the previous 15 years.
When a new car comes out on the market, these companies start working.
This is a very difficult task, because it is necessary to catalogue each of the thousand parts of the vehicle and record its price.
In addition, a "smart" graphic image of each model is created on which you can click on the different parts of a passenger car.
If it is a massively sold model, the work can be ready in a week if the process moves very quickly.
If it is a low-sold car, it can take three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
Among the most exclusive models, they have information about Porsches, but not Ferraris or Lamborghini.
For vehicles in use, the figure exceeds 99%.
To carry out the work of documentation and development of the databases, Audatex has eight centres throughout the world (in Spain, France, Germany, the United States, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), and each of them specializes in certain brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas, Madrid.
There, more than 100 technicians (usually mechanical experts) work simultaneously on three computer screens.
Audatex invests $90 million each year to develop these databases.
Every month, 2.5 million data are recorded, and customers receive updates every two days.
The development of this huge flow of information allows these companies to give them different uses and to offer various products.
The most common application is for repair and maintenance, but depending on the country, there are also tools for the management of break parts or for calculating the venal or residual value of a car.
